🔐 Digital Signatures, PKI & TLS
1. Introduction

When you visit:

https://google.com

your browser must answer three important questions before sending sensitive information like passwords or credit card details.

Am I really talking to Google?
Has anyone modified the data during transmission?
Can attackers read my communication?

Digital Signatures, Public Key Infrastructure (PKI), Certificates, and TLS work together to answer these questions.

2. Digital Signature
Definition

A Digital Signature is a cryptographic technique that provides:

Authentication
Integrity
Non-Repudiation

Unlike encryption, the purpose of a Digital Signature is not to hide data.

Instead, it proves:

Who sent the message.
That the message has not been modified.
Why Do We Need Digital Signatures?

Suppose Alice sends Bob:

Transfer ₹1000

An attacker intercepts the message and changes it to:

Transfer ₹10000

Without a Digital Signature:

Bob cannot detect the modification.

With a Digital Signature:

The change is immediately detected because the signature becomes invalid.

Real-Life Analogy

Think of signing a legal document.

Your handwritten signature proves:

You approved the document.
The document should not be modified afterwards.

Digital Signatures provide the same guarantee electronically.

3. How Digital Signatures Work

Suppose Alice wants to send Bob:

Hello Bob
Step 1 – Create a Hash
Message

